The ORR performance was tested in O2-saturated 0.1 M KOH solution with the catalyst loaded on GC electrode of 0.46 mg cm−2. Fig. 4
                     a gives the ORR steady-state polarization curves, in which the more positive values of onset potential (Eonset) and the half-wave potential (E1/2) predict better ORR activity. The corresponding mass activities of Pd-based catalysts including Pt/C calculated are shown in Fig. 4b. All prepared Pd-based catalysts exhibit prominently enhanced ORR properties with higher Eonset and more positive E1/2 than that of the supports themselves pre-reported by our group [37], indicating that the reduced Pd atoms act as the main active sites for ORR. And these Pd-based catalysts present high ORR activity with close Eonset and E1/2 to that of Pt/C (Fig. 4a) and demonstrate higher mass activities than commercial Pt/C catalyst (Fig. 4b), revealing that the methanol-reduced technology is an effective method for synthesis of high active Pd nanostructure. The clean Pd surface, the lower crystallinity and the surface distortion formed in methanol-reduced system maybe contributed to their prominent ORR activity. Among these Pd-based catalysts, Pd/B,N-CDs@CNT catalyst has the highest E1/2 (0.89 V vs RHE) much closed to that of the Pt/C (0.896 V vs RHE, Fig. 4a). Surprisingly, the Pd/B,N-CDs@CNT possesses the optimal mass activity of about 0.90 A per mgPd, surpassing the Pt/C catalyst (0.17 A per mgPt) by ca.5-6 times under 0.86 V Vs RHE. The ORR performance of Pd/B,N-CDs@CNT was compared with various Pd-based catalysts in reported literature (Table 1
                     ). Herein, the Pd/B,N-CDs@CNT shows much higher ORR mass activity (0.22 A per mgPd at 0.91 V) than that of the commercial Pd/C catalyst (about 0.05 A per mgPd at 0.9 V) [46]. Importantly, the Pd/B,N-CDs@CNT exhibits higher or comparable Eonset, E1/2 and mass activity relative to the developed Pd-based catalysts [15,28,41,47–52]. The tafel slopes of Pd/B,N-CDs@CNT, Pd/B-CNT, Pd/N-CNT and Pd/CNT based on the ORR polarization curves are 60, 74, 66 and 71 mV dec−1, in which the Pd/B,N-CDs@CNT gives the lowest tafel slope closer to that of Pt/C (64 mV dec−1, Fig. 4c). Hence, the B,N-CDs@CNT compound is an efficient support to enhance the Pd ORR performance. The composited B,N-CDs into CNT including the B, N doping has an important impact on the ORR activity of the catalysts, in which the B,N-CDs can supply more adsorbed sites and the doped B, N atoms can reduce the strong interaction of Pd with carbon, then releasing more Pd active sites and thus promoting the ORR performance. The N doped into CNT can better anchor the Pd atoms and the N–Pd bonds are conducive to the transfer of electrons. The synergistic effect of B and N co-doping also contributes to the prominent ORR performance of Pd/B,N-CDs@CNT. The electron transfer number (n) and hydrogen peroxide (H2O2) yield of Pd/B,N-CDs@CNT were calculated by RRDE experiment (Fig. 4d). In the 0.2–0.8 V, the average electron transfer number is 3.64, the H2O2 production rate is less than 30%. Along with increasing scanning potential, the H2O2 production rate decreases rapidly with less than 11% at 0.65 V. The results of RRDE test confirm that Pd/B,N-CDs@CNT was beneficial to the selectivity of ORR in the four-electron reaction.
